Citation.sTitle: Thermodynamic functions of hydrogen bonding of amines in methanol: head space  analysis and solution calorimetry
Citation.sAbstract: Reactivity and properties of organic molecules in self-associated liquids greatly depend on  the hydrogen bonding with solvent. Thus, the determination of the thermodynamic functions of  hydrogen bonding between solute and solvent molecules causes a practical interest. This work  contains an entire thermodynamic analysis of hydrogen bonding of aliphatic and aromatic amines in  associated solvent methanol. The enthalpies of solution at infinite dilution and limiting activity  coefficients for studied systems were measured experimentally for this purpose. Enthalpies and Gibbs  energies of specific interaction of amines with neat methanol were determined. These values were  found to be decreased comparing with thermodynamic functions of hydrogen bonding in equimolar  complexes "methanol-amine" determined in inert solvent or base media. The linear dependence  between enthalpies and Gibbs energies of specific interactions of amines with neat methanol was  observed. It was firstly revealed that the entropy of specific interactions of amines with neat methanol  can be about zero or positive. Obtained results show that one of the most important steps in the  process of dissolution of amine in methanol is the reorganization of solvent-solvent hydrogen bonds. It  was found, that the cooperative effect of adjacent hydrogen bonds has an impact on the Gibbs energies  of specific interaction of amines in methanol, but its value is significantly smaller than in water  solutions.  A new view on determination and analysis of thermodynamic functions of the specific interaction of  solute with methanol is presented in this work. The new results show that the process of hydrogen  bond formation in the self-associated solvents are significantly different from the hydrogen bonding in  the 1:1 complexes formed in aprotic solvents.
